{"title_page": "Raytheon Missiles & Defense", "text_new": "{{1r|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Raytheon Missiles & Defense\n| logo                = File:Raytheon Missiles & Defense logo red.svg\n| industry            = Aerospace and Defense\n| fate                = \n| predecessor         = Hughes Missile Systems Co.\n| successor           = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded             = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], country -->\n| founder             = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct             = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city    = [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = Wes Kremer, President\n| products            = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees       = \n| num_employees_year  = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent              = [[Raytheon Technologies]]\n| website             = {{URL|https://www.raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Raytheon Missiles & Defense''' is a subsidiary of [[Raytheon Technologies]]. Headquartered in Tucson, Arizona, its president is Wes Kremer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/about/leadership/wesley-kremer|title=Raytheon Missiles & Defense Website|last=Raytheon Missiles & Defense|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The business produces a broad portfolio of advanced technologies, including air and missile defense systems, precision weapons, radars, and command and control systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtx.com/Our-Company/Our-Businesses/RMD|title=Raytheon Technologies Business Overview|last=Raytheon Technologies Business Overview|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe business is a combination of two Raytheon Company legacy businesses, Raytheon Integrated Defense Systems and Raytheon Missile Systems, which operated a plant formerly owned by the '''Hughes Aircraft Company'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughes_Aircraft_Company|title=Hughes Aircraft Company Wiki Page|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'''.''' David Leighton, a noted historian, documented the early history of the Hughes Missile Plant in two books. His monograph: ''The Falcon's Nest: The Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947-1960'', which included the early history of Hughes Aircraft Co. and, his reference book: ''The History of the Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947\u20131960''.<ref>David Leighton, ''The Falcon's Nest: The Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947-1960,''Tucson Corral of the Westerners, 2017</ref><ref>David Leighton, ''The History of the Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947\u20131960.'' Private Publication, 2015</ref> \n\nThe division's products include:\n\n* [[AGM-65 Maverick]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-88 HARM]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-129 ACM]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-154 Joint Standoff Weapon]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-176 Griffin]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AIM-7 Sparrow]] air-to-air missile\n** [[RIM-7 Sea Sparrow]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-9 Sidewinder]] air-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-54 Phoenix]] air-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-120 AMRAAM]] air-to-air missile\n* [[BGM-71 TOW]] anti-tank missile\n* [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] cruise missile\n* [[Raytheon Coyote|Coyote]] unmanned aerial system\n* [[Extended Range Guided Munition]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070825084348/http://www.raytheon.com/products/ergm/]\n* [[Exoatmospheric Kill Vehicle]] anti ICBM system\n* [[FGM-148 Javelin]] anti-tank missile\n* [[FIM-92 Stinger]] Man-Portable Air-Defense System surface-to-air missile\n* [[M982 Excalibur]] guided artillery round\n* [[MIM-23 Hawk]] surface-to-air missile\n* [[MIM-104 Patriot]] surface-to-air missile\n* [[Paveway]] laser-guided bomb\n* [[Phalanx CIWS]] naval anti-missile defense system\n* [[RIM-116 Rolling Airframe Missile]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* [[RIM-162 ESSM|RIM-162 Evolved Sea Sparrow Missile]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* Standard Missile family of naval missiles\n** [[RIM-66 Standard]]\n** [[RIM-67 Standard]]\n** [[RIM-161 Standard Missile 3]]\n** [[RIM-174 Standard ERAM]]\n* [[SAM-N-2 Lark]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/}}\n\n{{Raytheon Technologies}}\n{{Raytheon}}\n\n[[Category:Raytheon]]\n[[Category:Guided missile manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Defense companies of the United States]]\n\n{{manufacturing-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{1r|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Raytheon Missiles & Defense\n| logo                = File:Raytheon Missiles & Defense logo red.svg\n| industry            = Aerospace and Defense\n| fate                = \n| predecessor         = Hughes Missile Systems Co.\n| successor           = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded             = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], country -->\n| founder             = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct             = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city    = [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = Wes Kremer, President\n| products            = \n| owner               = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees       = \n| num_employees_year  = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent              = [[Raytheon Technologies]]\n| website             = {{URL|https://www.raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Raytheon Missiles & Defense''' is a subsidiary of [[Raytheon Technologies]]. Headquartered in Tucson, Arizona, its president is Wes Kremer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/about/leadership/wesley-kremer|title=Raytheon Missiles & Defense Website|last=Raytheon Missiles & Defense|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. The business produces a broad portfolio of advanced technologies, including air and missile defense systems, precision weapons, radars, and command and control systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtx.com/Our-Company/Our-Businesses/RMD|title=Raytheon Technologies Business Overview|last=Raytheon Technologies Business Overview|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe business is a combination of two Raytheon Company legacy businesses, Raytheon Integrated Defense Systems, and Raytheon Missile Systems, formerly known as '''Hughes Aircraft Company'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hughes_Aircraft_Company|title=Hughes Aircraft Company Wiki Page|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>'''.''' David Leighton, a noted historian, documented the early history of the Hughes Missile Plant in two books. His monograph: ''The Falcon's Nest: The Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947-1960'', which included the early history of Hughes Aircraft Co. and, his reference book: ''The History of the Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947\u20131960''.<ref>David Leighton, ''The Falcon's Nest: The Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947-1960,''Tucson Corral of the Westerners, 2017</ref><ref>David Leighton, ''The History of the Hughes Missile Plant in Tucson, 1947\u20131960.'' Private Publication, 2015</ref> \n\nThe division's products include:\n\n* [[AGM-65 Maverick]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-88 HARM]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-129 ACM]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-154 Joint Standoff Weapon]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AGM-176 Griffin]] air-to-surface missile\n* [[AIM-7 Sparrow]] air-to-air missile\n** [[RIM-7 Sea Sparrow]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-9 Sidewinder]] air-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-54 Phoenix]] air-to-air missile\n* [[AIM-120 AMRAAM]] air-to-air missile\n* [[BGM-71 TOW]] anti-tank missile\n* [[BGM-109 Tomahawk]] cruise missile\n* [[Raytheon Coyote|Coyote]] unmanned aerial system\n* [[Extended Range Guided Munition]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070825084348/http://www.raytheon.com/products/ergm/]\n* [[Exoatmospheric Kill Vehicle]] anti ICBM system\n* [[FGM-148 Javelin]] anti-tank missile\n* [[FIM-92 Stinger]] Man-Portable Air-Defense System surface-to-air missile\n* [[M982 Excalibur]] guided artillery round\n* [[MIM-23 Hawk]] surface-to-air missile\n* [[MIM-104 Patriot]] surface-to-air missile\n* [[Paveway]] laser-guided bomb\n* [[Phalanx CIWS]] naval anti-missile defense system\n* [[RIM-116 Rolling Airframe Missile]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* [[RIM-162 ESSM|RIM-162 Evolved Sea Sparrow Missile]] naval surface-to-air missile\n* Standard Missile family of naval missiles\n** [[RIM-66 Standard]]\n** [[RIM-67 Standard]]\n** [[RIM-161 Standard Missile 3]]\n** [[RIM-174 Standard ERAM]]\n* [[SAM-N-2 Lark]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.raytheonmissilesanddefense.com/}}\n\n{{Raytheon Technologies}}\n{{Raytheon}}\n\n[[Category:Raytheon]]\n[[Category:Guided missile manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Defense companies of the United States]]\n\n{{manufacturing-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MurphyPQ12", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raytheon_Missiles_%26_Defense"}
{"title_page": "Collett (name)", "text_new": "'''Collett''' is both a surname and a given name. Notable people with the name include:\n\n* [[Collett (Norwegian family)]], including\n** [[Axel Collett]], Norwegian landowner\n** [[Camilla Collett]] (1813\u20131895), Norwegian author\n** [[Johan Collett]] (1775\u20131827), Norwegian politician\n** [[Johan Christian Collett]] (1817\u20131895), Norwegian politician, son of Johan Collett\n** [[Jonas Collett]] (1772\u20131851), Norwegian politician\n** [[Robert Collett]] (1842\u20131913), Norwegian zoologist\n\n'''Other people with Collett as a surname:'''\n* [[Andy Collett]] (born 1973), English retired football goalkeeper\n* [[Anthony Collett]] (1877\u20131929), English author\n* [[Ben Collett]] (born 1984), English footballer\n* [[Charles Collett]] (1851\u20131952), British chief mechanical engineer of the Great Western Railway\n* [[Charles E. Collett]], American lawyer and 1924 Olympic water polo team member\n* [[Charlie Collett]] (born 2004), World War I flying ace from New Zealand\n* [[Elmer Collett]] (born 1944), American football player\n* [[Ernie Collett (disambiguation)]], several people\n* [[Gilbert Collett]] (1879\u20131945), English rugby union player\n* [[Glenna Collett-Vare]] (1903\u20131989), American golfing champion\n* Sir [[Henry Collett]] (1836\u20131901), army officer in the East India Company and botanist\n* [[Herbert Collett]] (1877\u20131947), Australian politician and soldier\n* [[Jason Collett]], Canadian musician\n* [[John Collett (artist)]] (1725\u20131780), English painter\n* [[Joseph Collett]] (1673\u20131725), British East India Company administrator, Governor of Bencoolen and President of Madras\n* [[Lorraine Collett]] (1892\u20131983), American model, the \"Sun-Maid girl\"\n* [[Lucy Collett]], (born 1989), British glamour model \n* [[Mark Collett]] (born 1980), British political activist\n* [[Nathan Collett]], Kenyan filmmaker\n* [[Ritter Collett]] (1921\u20132001), American sports editor a