th     = {{Duration|m=74|s=10}}\n| label      = Rip-it\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[The Wait is Over]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = 199Quad\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Tootsee Roll]]\n | single1date = May 31, 1994\n | single2     = Kitty Kitty\n | single2date = 1994\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r203094|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''199Quad''''' is the debut album of the [[Southern rap]] group [[69 Boyz]], released in 1994 following the success of their song \"[[Tootsee Roll]]\".  The album peaked at number 59 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on April 1, 1995. The album was re-released with a new cover and a bonus DVD by [[Lil Joe]] on October 10, 2006. On July 11, 1995, the album was certified Platinum by the RIAA for selling 1,000,000 copies.\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Tracklist\n| all_writing = Da S.W.A.T. Team (Jay McGowan and Van Bryant)\n| total_length = 74:10\n| title1 = Land 69\n| length1 = 1:07\n| title2 = Caller #10\n| length2 = 0:47\n| title3 = Da Train\n| length3 = 4:29\n| title4 = Loose Booty\n| length4 = 4:07\n| title5 = Kitty Kitty\n| length5 = 4:10\n| title6 = Puddin Tame\n| length6 = 3:29\n| title7 = Da Set\n| length7 = 2:25\n| title8 = Hennessy\n| length8 = 1:37\n| title9 = Survival of da Fittest\n| length9 = 5:55\n| title10 = Hump N' Ya Back\n| length10 = 2:58\n| title11 = Get Together\n| length11 = 3:53\n| title12 = Tootsee Roll\n| length12 = 4:18\n| title13 = Da Mote\n| length13 = 4:33\n| title14 = Ding Dong Song\n| length14 = 4:10\n| title15 = Teenie Weenie\n| length15 = 3:05\n| title16 = 10 Chicken Wangs and A Bottle of Dom\n| length16 = 3:24\n| title17 = Ease on Down da Road\n| length17 = 4:57\n| title18 = Booty Drop\n| length18 = 3:26\n| title19 = All Men R Dawgs\n| length19 = 3:06\n| title20 = Buddy-Buddy\n| length20 = 3:53\n| title21 = Tootsee Roll\n| note21 = Dance Version\n| length21 = 4:21\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1995)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHeatseekers|1|artist=69 Boyz|refname=BB1|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|13|artist=69 Boyz|refname=BB2|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|59|artist=69 Boyz|refname=BB3|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Nineteen Ninety Quad|artist=69 Boyz|type=album|certyear=1995|certmonth=17 |certday=11|region=United States|award=Platinum}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:199quad}}\n[[Category:69 Boyz albums]]\n[[Category:1994 debut albums]]\n{{1990s-hiphop-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "HowlinMadMan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added cite reference for RIAA certification.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/199Quad"}
{"title_page": "Nyhavn", "text_new": "{{Attached KML}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name            = Nyhavn\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Nyhavn MichaD.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = Colourful facade and old ships along the Nyhavn Canal\n| former_names    = \n| location        = [[Indre By]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| postal_code     = 1051\n| length_m        = 450\n| width           =\n| metro                   = [[Kongens Nytorv station|Kongens Nytorv]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|47|N|12|35|26|E}}\n}}\n'''Nyhavn''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8ny\u02cch\u0251w\u02c0n}}; New Harbour) is a 17th-century waterfront, canal and entertainment district in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Stretching from [[Kongens Nytorv]] to the harbour front just south of the [[Royal Danish Playhouse|Royal Playhouse]], it is lined by brightly coloured 17th and early 18th century [[townhouse]]s and bars, cafes and restaurants. The canal harbours many historical wooden ships.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Nyhavn (Rosens Kort, 1674(.jpg|thumb|160px|Nyhavn seen on a detail from Rosen's Map of Copenhagen, 1674]]\nNyhavn was constructed by [[Christian V of Denmark|King Christian V]] from 1670 to 1675, dug by Swedish prisoners of war from the [[Dano-Swedish War (1658\u20131660)|Dano-Swedish War 1658\u20131660]]. It is a gateway from the sea to the old inner city at [[Kongens Nytorv]] (King's Square), where ships handled cargo and fishermens' catch. It was notorious for beer, sailors, and prostitution. Danish author [[Hans Christian Andersen]] lived at Nyhavn for some 18 years.\n\nThe first bridge across Nyhavn opened on [[1874 in Denmark|1874]]. It was a temporary wooden footbridge. It was replaced by the current bridge in 1912.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyhavns-skipperlaug.dk/Wikka/wikka.php?wakka=AnDet |title=Nyhavns historie |language=Danish |work=Nyhavns Skipperlaug |accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nyhavn, Copenhagen (Denmark) 01.jpg|left|thumb|The canal]]\nAs ocean-going ships grew larger, Nyhavn was taken over by internal Danish small vessel freight traffic. After World War II land transport took over this role and small vessel traffic disappeared from the Port of Copenhagen, leaving Nyhavn largely deserted of ships.\n\nIn the mid-1960s, the Nyhavn Society (Danish: Nyhavnsforeningen) was founded with the aim of revitalising the area. In 1977, Nyhavn was inaugurated as a veteran ship and museum harbour by Copenhagen's Lord Mayor [[Egon Weidekamp]]. In 1980 Nyhavn quay was [[pedestrianised]]; it had been used as a parking area in the previous years which had coincided with a dwindling of harbour activities.<ref name=publicspaces >{{cite book |last1=Gehl |first1=Jan |last2=Gemz\u00f8e |first2=Lars |title=Public Spaces, Public Life, Copenhagen |year=1996 |isbn=877-407-305-2 |publisher=The Danish Noob Architectural Press and the Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts |page=20}}</ref> Since then it has become a popular spot for tourists and locals alike, serving the function of a square according to architects [[Jan Gehl]] and Lars Gemz\u00f8e.<ref name=publicspaces />\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Nyhavn, Copenhagen, Denmark.jpg|thumb|600 px|Panorama of north side of Nyhavn]]\nThe northern side of Nyhavn is lined by brightly coloured townhouses built with wood, bricks, and plaster. The oldest house, at No. 9, dates from 1681.\n\nBetween 1845 and 1864, [[Hans Christian Andersen]] lived at [[Nyhavn 67|No. 67]], where a memorial plaque now stands. From 1871-1875 Andersen lived at Nyhavn 18,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://visithcandersen.dk/nyhavn_18.htm/ |title=Nyhavn 18 |work=H. C. Andersen Information |accessdate=31 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416161134/http://www.visithcandersen.dk/nyhavn_18.htm |archivedate=16 April 2017 }}</ref> which currently houses an Andersen-themed souvenir shop.\n\nThe southern side of Nyhavn has lavish mansions lining the canal, including [[Charlottenborg Palace]] at the corner of Kongens Nytorv.\n\n==Veteran Ship and Museum Harbour==\n[[File:Nyhavn pano.jpg|thumb|600 px|Panorama looking across Nyhavn, from south side to north, with the lightship in foreground, and other museum ships]]\nNyhavn Veteran Ship and Museum Harbour, occupying the inner section of Nyhavn, between the Nyhavn Bridge and Kongens Nytorv, is lined with old ships. From the foundation of the heritage harbour in 1977, the south side of the canal has been reserved for museum ships owned by the [[National Museum of Denmark|Danish National Museum]], which received a donation of carefully restored ships from [[A. P. Moller-Maersk Group|A. P. M\u00f8ller]], while the northern side of the canal was put at the disposal of the Nyhavn Society and privately owned, still usable wooden ships.\nHarbor ships include:\n* ''[[Lightvessel Gedser Rev|Lightvessel XVII Gedser Rev]]'' \u2013 [[lightvessel]] built in [[Odense]] in 1895, in operation until 1972, then acquired by the National Museum and now serving as a museum ship.\n* ''Svalan af Nyhavn'' \u2013 [[galleass]] built in Jungfrusund in 1924\n* ''Anna M\u00f8ller'' \u2013 galleass built in [[Randers]] in 1906\n* ''MA-RI'' \u2013 purpose-built smuggling ship built in 1920; [[Boarding (attack)|boarded]] by custom authorities off [[Helsing\u00f8r|Elsinore]] with smuggling goods aboard in 1923, then confiscated and sold on auction, then operated both as a fishing vessel and as a ferry between [[Poland]] and [[Bornholm]], again as a smuggling vessel.\n* ''Mira'' \u2013 two-masted [[schooner]] built in [[F\u00e5borg]] in 1898, considered one of the finest ships of the Danish small vessel traffic of the time. For many years it transported [[chalk]] from [[Stevns Peninsula|Stevns]]. The first ship on the north side of Nyhavn, coming from Kongens Nytorv.\n* ''[[B\u00e5dteatret|The Boat Theatre]]'' - a [[Lighter (barge)|lighter]]-type [[barge]] built in Copenhagen in 1898, since 1972 operated as a theatre boat.\n\n==The Memorial Anchor==\n[[Image:Anker Nyhavn.jpg|right|thumb|The Memorial Anchor at the end of Nyhavn]]\nThe great Memorial Anchor (Danish: Mindeankeret) at the end of Nyhavn, where it meets Kongens Nytorv, is a monument commemorating the more than 1,700 Danish officers and sailors in service for the [[Royal Danish Navy|Navy]], merchant fleet or [[Allies of World War II|Allied Forces]], who sacrificed their lives during [[World War II]]. The Anchor was inaugurated in 1951, replacing a temporary wooden cross erected on the spot in 1945, and has a plaque with a monogram of King [[Frederik VII of Denmark|Frederik VII]] on it. The Memorial Anchor is from 1872 and was used on the Frigate Fyn (Funen), which was docked at [[Holmen Naval Base]] during the Second World War. Every year on May 5 \u2013 Denmark's Liberation day 1945 \u2013 an official ceremony is held to honour and commemorate the fallen at the Memorial Anchor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.copenhagenet.dk/CPH-Nyhavn.htm |title=Nyhavn |work=Copenhagen Portal |accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Bars and restaurants==\n[[Image:Nyhavn 24-6-2003.JPG|right|thumb|Bars and restaurants lining the northern, sunny side of Nyhavn]]\nAlong its northern, sunnier side, Nyhavn is lined with many bars and restaurants facing the harbor.  Nyhavn serves as a hub of canal tours, but it can be chilly.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Kongens Nytorv station|Kongens Nytorv metro station]] is located at the end of Nyhavn, though situated at the far end of the namesake square outside [[Magasin du Nord]]. The station is served by both lines [[M1 (Copenhagen)|M1]] and [[M2 (Copenhagen)|M2]] of the [[Copenhagen Metro]].\n\nThe [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses]] has a stop at the mouth of Nyhavn. All four routes of the harbour buses, [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#901 & 902|Routes 901, 902]], [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#903|903]] and [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#904|904]], stop at the bus stop next to the [[Royal Danish Playhouse|Royal Playhouse]].\n\nIn 2016 the [[Inderhavnsbroen|Inner Harbor Bridge]] (Inderhavnsbro) connecting Nyhavn and Christianshavn was opened after years of setbacks and delays. The 180 m cycling and pedestrian [[drawbridge]] has been nicknamed the Kissing Bridge because its contour resembles two tongues meeting.<ref>{{cite web |title=Surprise! Long-delayed Copenhagen Bridge Opens |url=http://www.thelocal.dk/20160708/copenhagen-inner-harbour-bridge-inderhavnsbroen-opens |date=8 July 2016  |work=[[The Local]] DK |accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\n===Film===\n* Nyhavn has been seen in numerous Danish films. It is for instance used as a location in a number of ''[[Olsen-banden]]'' films, for instance at 0:25:44 in ''[[The Olsen Gang on the Track]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 7 Olsen banden p\u00e5 sporet / Die Olsenbande stellt die Weichen|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> and at 0:28:56 in the 1977 [[Olsen Gang]] film ''[[The Olsen Gang Outta Sight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 9 Olsen Banden deruda / Die Olsenbande schl\u00e4gt wieder zu|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> The Memorial Anchor is seen at 1:16:57 in ''[[The Olsen Gang Sees Red]]''..<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 8 Olsen Banden ser r\u00f8dt / Die Olsenbande sieht rot|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nNyhavn has also been featured in a number of international films.\n* The closing scenes of [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s ''[[A Lesson in Love]]'' takes place in Nyhavn.<ref name=Filmby>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekkofilm.dk/artikler/filmby-copenhagen/|title=Filmby Copenhagen|website=Ekko|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n* In the 1957 British-American action film ''[[Hidden Fear]]'', Nyhavn is used as a central location.\n* In the 1963 German film ''[[The Lightship (1963 film)|The Lightship]]'', Nyhavn is used as a location in spite of the fact that the film is set in Germany.\n* In the 1966 [[Alfred Hitchcock]] spy film ''[[Torn Curtain]]'', Curtain ([[Paul Newman]]), who is on the way to DDR, is told to contact a used book seller at Kanalgade 1 which later turns out to be Nyhavn when his fianc\u00e9e (Julie Andrews) visits the address.<ref name=Filmby/>\n* In the 2015 drama film ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'', Nyhavn is the location where [[Lili Elbe|Einar]] ([[Eddie Redmayne]]) and [[Gerda Wegener|Gerda]] ([[Alicia Vikander]]) live, and it is also where Lili makes her first forays in public. Nyhavn is in the film presented as a fish market while Copenhagen's historic fish market was in fact located at [[Gammel Strand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitdenmark.com/denmark/tour-danish-girl-locations|title=Tour The Danish Girl locations|website=visitdenmark.dk|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\n* Elisabeth Levy's 1997 novel ''Et dukkehus i Nyhavn'' (''A Doll House in Nyhavn'') describes a young girls life in Nyhavn in 1929.\n* [[Anne Marie Ejrn\u00e6s]]'s 2002 biographical novel ''Som Svalen'' (''Like the Swallow'') about [[Thomasine Christine Gyllembourg-Ehrensv\u00e4rd|Thomasine Gyllenbourg]] begins when she is eight years old and lives in her father's home at [[Nyhavn 67]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gyldendal.dk/produkter/anne-marie-ejrn\u00e6s/som-svalen-42032/andet-9788702206463|title=Som svanen|language=Danish|website=Gyldendal|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Karin Micha\u00eblis]]'s 1936 children's book ''Lotte Ligeglad'' is about a girl who lives in Nyhavn where her mother owns a shop next to a tavern.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Historien_om_b\u00f8rnelitteratur/B\u00f8rnene,_de_v\u00e6rgel\u00f8se_-__b\u00f8rnelitteraturen_1918-1964/Pigeromanerne/Karin_Michaelis|title=Karin Micha\u00eblislocations|website=denstoredanske.dk|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n* ''Nu g\u00e5r v\u00e5ren gennem Nyhavn'' is a song by Sigfred Pedersen with melody by [[Niels Clemmensen]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tourism in Denmark]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.copenhagenet.dk/CPH-Map/CPH-Nyhavn.asp Copenhagen-Portal - Nyhavn]\n* [http://rejsefortaelling.dk/nyhavns_huse/nyhavns_huse.htm Source]\n\n{{Indre By Copenhagen}}\n{{coord|55|40|47|N|12|35|26|E|region:DK_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Copenhagen}}\n\n[[Category:Canals in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Restaurant districts and streets]]\n[[Category:Entertainment districts in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Port of Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Canals opened in 1673]]\n[[Category:1673 establishments in Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{Attached KML}}\n{{Infobox street\n| name            = Nyhavn\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Nyhavn MichaD.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = Colourful facade and old ships along the Nyhavn Canal\n| former_names    = \n| location        = [[Indre By]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| postal_code     = 1051\n| length_m        = 450\n| width           =\n| metro                   = [[Kongens Nytorv station|Kongens Nytorv]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|47|N|12|35|26|E}}\n}}\n'''Nyhavn''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8ny\u02cchaw\u02c0n}}; New Harbour) is a 17th-century waterfront, canal and entertainment district in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Stretching from [[Kongens Nytorv]] to the harbour front just south of the [[Royal Danish Playhouse|Royal Playhouse]], it is lined by brightly coloured 17th and early 18th century [[townhouse]]s and bars, cafes and restaurants. The canal harbours many historical wooden ships.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Nyhavn (Rosens Kort, 1674(.jpg|thumb|160px|Nyhavn seen on a detail from Rosen's Map of Copenhagen, 1674]]\nNyhavn was constructed by [[Christian V of Denmark|King Christian V]] from 1670 to 1675, dug by Swedish prisoners of war from the [[Dano-Swedish War (1658\u20131660)|Dano-Swedish War 1658\u20131660]]. It is a gateway from the sea to the old inner city at [[Kongens Nytorv]] (King's Square), where ships handled cargo and fishermens' catch. It was notorious for beer, sailors, and prostitution. Danish author [[Hans Christian Andersen]] lived at Nyhavn for some 18 years.\n\nThe first bridge across Nyhavn opened on [[1874 in Denmark|1874]]. It was a temporary wooden footbridge. It was replaced by the current bridge in 1912.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyhavns-skipperlaug.dk/Wikka/wikka.php?wakka=AnDet |title=Nyhavns historie |language=Danish |work=Nyhavns Skipperlaug |accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nyhavn, Copenhagen (Denmark) 01.jpg|left|thumb|The canal]]\nAs ocean-going ships grew larger, Nyhavn was taken over by internal Danish small vessel freight traffic. After World War II land transport took over this role and small vessel traffic disappeared from the Port of Copenhagen, leaving Nyhavn largely deserted of ships.\n\nIn the mid-1960s, the Nyhavn Society (Danish: Nyhavnsforeningen) was founded with the aim of revitalising the area. In 1977, Nyhavn was inaugurated as a veteran ship and museum harbour by Copenhagen's Lord Mayor [[Egon Weidekamp]]. In 1980 Nyhavn quay was [[pedestrianised]]; it had been used as a parking area in the previous years which had coincided with a dwindling of harbour activities.<ref name=publicspaces >{{cite book |last1=Gehl |first1=Jan |last2=Gemz\u00f8e |first2=Lars |title=Public Spaces, Public Life, Copenhagen |year=1996 |isbn=877-407-305-2 |publisher=The Danish Noob Architectural Press and the Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts |page=20}}</ref> Since then it has become a popular spot for tourists and locals alike, serving the function of a square according to architects [[Jan Gehl]] and Lars Gemz\u00f8e.<ref name=publicspaces />\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Nyhavn, Copenhagen, Denmark.jpg|thumb|600 px|Panorama of north side of Nyhavn]]\nThe northern side of Nyhavn is lined by brightly coloured townhouses built with wood, bricks, and plaster. The oldest house, at No. 9, dates from 1681.\n\nBetween 1845 and 1864, [[Hans Christian Andersen]] lived at [[Nyhavn 67|No. 67]], where a memorial plaque now stands. From 1871-1875 Andersen lived at Nyhavn 18,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://visithcandersen.dk/nyhavn_18.htm/ |title=Nyhavn 18 |work=H. C. Andersen Information |accessdate=31 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416161134/http://www.visithcandersen.dk/nyhavn_18.htm |archivedate=16 April 2017 }}</ref> which currently houses an Andersen-themed souvenir shop.\n\nThe southern side of Nyhavn has lavish mansions lining the canal, including [[Charlottenborg Palace]] at the corner of Kongens Nytorv.\n\n==Veteran Ship and Museum Harbour==\n[[File:Nyhavn pano.jpg|thumb|600 px|Panorama looking across Nyhavn, from south side to north, with the lightship in foreground, and other museum ships]]\nNyhavn Veteran Ship and Museum Harbour, occupying the inner section of Nyhavn, between the Nyhavn Bridge and Kongens Nytorv, is lined with old ships. From the foundation of the heritage harbour in 1977, the south side of the canal has been reserved for museum ships owned by the [[National Museum of Denmark|Danish National Museum]], which received a donation of carefully restored ships from [[A. P. Moller-Maersk Group|A. P. M\u00f8ller]], while the northern side of the canal was put at the disposal of the Nyhavn Society and privately owned, still usable wooden ships.\nHarbor ships include:\n* ''[[Lightvessel Gedser Rev|Lightvessel XVII Gedser Rev]]'' \u2013 [[lightvessel]] built in [[Odense]] in 1895, in operation until 1972, then acquired by the National Museum and now serving as a museum ship.\n* ''Svalan af Nyhavn'' \u2013 [[galleass]] built in Jungfrusund in 1924\n* ''Anna M\u00f8ller'' \u2013 galleass built in [[Randers]] in 1906\n* ''MA-RI'' \u2013 purpose-built smuggling ship built in 1920; [[Boarding (attack)|boarded]] by custom authorities off [[Helsing\u00f8r|Elsinore]] with smuggling goods aboard in 1923, then confiscated and sold on auction, then operated both as a fishing vessel and as a ferry between [[Poland]] and [[Bornholm]], again as a smuggling vessel.\n* ''Mira'' \u2013 two-masted [[schooner]] built in [[F\u00e5borg]] in 1898, considered one of the finest ships of the Danish small vessel traffic of the time. For many years it transported [[chalk]] from [[Stevns Peninsula|Stevns]]. The first ship on the north side of Nyhavn, coming from Kongens Nytorv.\n* ''[[B\u00e5dteatret|The Boat Theatre]]'' - a [[Lighter (barge)|lighter]]-type [[barge]] built in Copenhagen in 1898, since 1972 operated as a theatre boat.\n\n==The Memorial Anchor==\n[[Image:Anker Nyhavn.jpg|right|thumb|The Memorial Anchor at the end of Nyhavn]]\nThe great Memorial Anchor (Danish: Mindeankeret) at the end of Nyhavn, where it meets Kongens Nytorv, is a monument commemorating the more than 1,700 Danish officers and sailors in service for the [[Royal Danish Navy|Navy]], merchant fleet or [[Allies of World War II|Allied Forces]], who sacrificed their lives during [[World War II]]. The Anchor was inaugurated in 1951, replacing a temporary wooden cross erected on the spot in 1945, and has a plaque with a monogram of King [[Frederik VII of Denmark|Frederik VII]] on it. The Memorial Anchor is from 1872 and was used on the Frigate Fyn (Funen), which was docked at [[Holmen Naval Base]] during the Second World War. Every year on May 5 \u2013 Denmark's Liberation day 1945 \u2013 an official ceremony is held to honour and commemorate the fallen at the Memorial Anchor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.copenhagenet.dk/CPH-Nyhavn.htm |title=Nyhavn |work=Copenhagen Portal |accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Bars and restaurants==\n[[Image:Nyhavn 24-6-2003.JPG|right|thumb|Bars and restaurants lining the northern, sunny side of Nyhavn]]\nAlong its northern, sunnier side, Nyhavn is lined with many bars and restaurants facing the harbor.  Nyhavn serves as a hub of canal tours, but it can be chilly.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Kongens Nytorv station|Kongens Nytorv metro station]] is located at the end of Nyhavn, though situated at the far end of the namesake square outside [[Magasin du Nord]]. The station is served by both lines [[M1 (Copenhagen)|M1]] and [[M2 (Copenhagen)|M2]] of the [[Copenhagen Metro]].\n\nThe [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses]] has a stop at the mouth of Nyhavn. All four routes of the harbour buses, [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#901 & 902|Routes 901, 902]], [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#903|903]] and [[Copenhagen Harbour Buses#904|904]], stop at the bus stop next to the [[Royal Danish Playhouse|Royal Playhouse]].\n\nIn 2016 the [[Inderhavnsbroen|Inner Harbor Bridge]] (Inderhavnsbro) connecting Nyhavn and Christianshavn was opened after years of setbacks and delays. The 180 m cycling and pedestrian [[drawbridge]] has been nicknamed the Kissing Bridge because its contour resembles two tongues meeting.<ref>{{cite web |title=Surprise! Long-delayed Copenhagen Bridge Opens |url=http://www.thelocal.dk/20160708/copenhagen-inner-harbour-bridge-inderhavnsbroen-opens |date=8 July 2016  |work=[[The Local]] DK |accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\n===Film===\n* Nyhavn has been seen in numerous Danish films. It is for instance used as a location in a number of ''[[Olsen-banden]]'' films, for instance at 0:25:44 in ''[[The Olsen Gang on the Track]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 7 Olsen banden p\u00e5 sporet / Die Olsenbande stellt die Weichen|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> and at 0:28:56 in the 1977 [[Olsen Gang]] film ''[[The Olsen Gang Outta Sight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 9 Olsen Banden deruda / Die Olsenbande schl\u00e4gt wieder zu|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> The Memorial Anchor is seen at 1:16:57 in ''[[The Olsen Gang Sees Red]]''..<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 8 Olsen Banden ser r\u00f8dt / Die Olsenbande sieht rot|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nNyhavn has also been featured in a number of international films.\n* The closing scenes of [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s ''[[A Lesson in Love]]'' takes place in Nyhavn.<ref name=Filmby>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekkofilm.dk/artikler/filmby-copenhagen/|title=Filmby Copenhagen|website=Ekko|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n* In the 1957 British-American action film ''[[Hidden Fear]]'', Nyhavn is used as a central location.\n* In the 1963 German film ''[[The Lightship (1963 film)|The Lightship]]'', Nyhavn is used as a location in spite of the fact that the film is set in Germany.\n* In the 1966 [[Alfred Hitchcock]] spy film ''[[Torn Curtain]]'', Curtain ([[Paul Newman]]), who is on the way to DDR, is told to contact a used book seller at Kanalgade 1 which later turns out to be Nyhavn when his fianc\u00e9e (Julie Andrews) visits the address.<ref name=Filmby/>\n* In the 2015 drama film ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'', Nyhavn is the location where [[Lili Elbe|Einar]] ([[Eddie Redmayne]]) and [[Gerda Wegener|Gerda]] ([[Alicia Vikander]]) live, and it is also where Lili makes her first forays in public. Nyhavn is in the film presented as a fish market while Copenhagen's historic fish market was in fact located at [[Gammel Strand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitdenmark.com/denmark/tour-danish-girl-locations|title=Tour The Danish Girl locations|website=visitdenmark.dk|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\n* Elisabeth Levy's 1997 novel ''Et dukkehus i Nyhavn'' (''A Doll House in Nyhavn'') describes a young girls life in Nyhavn in 1929.\n* [[Anne Marie Ejrn\u00e6s]]'s 2002 biographical novel ''Som Svalen'' (''Like the Swallow'') about [[Thomasine Christine Gyllembourg-Ehrensv\u00e4rd|Thomasine Gyllenbourg]] begins when she is eight years old and lives in her father's home at [[Nyhavn 67]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gyldendal.dk/produkter/anne-marie-ejrn\u00e6s/som-svalen-42032/andet-9788702206463|title=Som svanen|language=Danish|website=Gyldendal|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Karin Micha\u00eblis]]'s 1936 children's book ''Lotte Ligeglad'' is about a girl who lives in Nyhavn where her mother owns a shop next to a tavern.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Historien_om_b\u00f8rnelitteratur/B\u00f8rnene,_de_v\u00e6rgel\u00f8se_-__b\u00f8rnelitteraturen_1918-1964/Pigeromanerne/Karin_Michaelis|title=Karin Micha\u00eblislocations|website=denstoredanske.dk|accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n* ''Nu g\u00e5r v\u00e5ren gennem Nyhavn'' is a song by Sigfred Pedersen with melody by [[Niels Clemmensen]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tourism in Denmark]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.copenhagenet.dk/CPH-Map/CPH-Nyhavn.asp Copenhagen-Portal - Nyhavn]\n* [http://rejsefortaelling.dk/nyhavns_huse/nyhavns_huse.htm Source]\n\n{{Indre By Copenhagen}}\n{{coord|55|40|47|N|12|35|26|E|region:DK_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Copenhagen}}\n\n[[Category:Canals in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Restaurant districts and streets]]\n[[Category:Entertainment districts in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Port of Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Canals opened in 1673]]\n[[Category:1673 establishments in Denmark]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyhavn"}
{"title_page": "Anna Catharina Bischoff", "text_new": "[[File:Anna_Catharina_Bischoff.jpeg|thumb|Mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff|700px]] \n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserkirche Treppe Fundort.jpeg|thumb|Where the coffin was found]]\n'''Anna Catharina Bischoff''' (born 23 March 1719 in [[Strasbourg]] and buried 30 August 1787 in [[Basel]]), also known as the \"Lady (or mummy) of the Barf\u00fcsser Church\" was the wife of the [[pastor]] Lucas Gernler. She gained popularity in 1975, when her [[Mummy|mummified]] corpse was found in a shaft at the Barf\u00fcsser Church in Basel.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 bbc news]</ref>\n\n==Past history==\n[[File:Barfuesserplatz 1788.jpg|thumb|Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1788]]\n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1835.jpg|thumb|Around 1835, when the church was used as a warehouse]]\n\nIn 1975, the Barf\u00fcsser Church underwent a thorough renovation, during which the archaeological department of the city of Basel excavated and documented hundreds of burial sites.\n\n==Discovery==\nOn 20 October 1975, workers discovered a brick-walled grave chamber in front of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]], containing two well-preserved coffins sitting on a pile of bones. The upper coffin contained the skeleton of a female while the smaller coffin beneath contained the completely mummified corpse of a woman, who would later be known as the \"Lady/Mummy of the Barf\u00fcsser Church.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/boris-johnson-mummy-swiss-corpse-relative-dna-anna-catharina-bischoff-syphilis-uk-foreign-secretary-a8177641.html Independent.co.uk 25 january 2018]</ref>\n\n==First examinations==\nThe woman was buried in a simple spruce wood coffin, her left hand holding her right arm above the wrist. The mummy was mostly intact: only the head and feet had decomposed while parts of her dress and hair were conserved. Her height was 142&nbsp;cm, which is small even by contemporary standards; skinfolds point at a stout body.\n\nA first examination in 1976 by [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Bruno Kaufmann revealed that [[Mercury sulfide]] (found in the whole body, especially in the lungs), prevented decay and was responsible for the mummification. Atmospheric conditions within the coffin and grave chamber also prevented [[microbes]] from breaking down the corpse.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 76ff (german)</ref>\n\n==Recent research==\nSince 2015, the mummy has been investigated using modern methods at the [[Natural History Museum of Basel]]. [[CT scan|Computer tomography]] revealed [[atherosclerosis]] of the abdominal [[aorta]] and [[gall stones|gallstones]], pointing at a diet consisting mainly of carbohydrates and fatty meat. During her lifetime, the woman had lost all the teeth in her upper jaw due to a sugary diet and oral hygiene neglect; her lower incisors and canines, although [[Tooth decay|decayed]], were preserved.\n[[File:Behandlung mit Quecksilberd\u00e4mpfen.jpeg|thumb|Treatment with mercury vapour. In a small chamber, mercury vapour was inhaled. Illustration of the 17th century]]\n\nThe detection of [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] in the lungs and other organs of Anna Catharina Bischoff led the medical historians of the 1970s to the conclusion that the woman had undergone a mercury inhalation therapy. In those days, it was the usual method of treatment, which, however, was only administered to patients with severe cases of [[syphilis]].<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Anna-Catharina/6000000044219255864 geni.com]</ref>\n\nModern analytical methods for measuring the level of mercury exposure indicate that the amount administered was below the threshold to have caused [[mercury poisoning]]. Mercury was indeed found in the body of Anna Catharina Bischoff, but with the data available at present, it is not possible to ascertain whether this had actually led to her death. Thus, the cause of her death cannot be proven beyond doubt. Further investigation is necessary to indicate whether this was caused by the syphilis or a combination of syphilis and mercury exposure. <ref>Report Thomas Briellmann, forensic toxicologist, University Basel</ref>\n\n==Identification== \n[[File:Aktennotiz Blendinger.jpg|thumb|upright|File note by contractor Blendinger]]\nAccording to the prominent position of her grave, it can be deduced that the deceased was a member of a privileged class\u2014the location was reserved for members of the high clergy or dignitaries.<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch of 25 january 2018 (German)]</ref>\n \nChurch archive documents show that the shaft in front of the choir had been opened once before 1843 when the nave of the church was transformed into a commercial warehouse. When the workers lifted the memorial slab labeled number 11, they discovered a grave underneath with three coffins. In 2016, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin, members of Basel's citizen-researchers who discover and transcribe historic sources, discovered the relevant text in contractor Blendinger's notes, describing the text on the memorial slab as follows (in the original in German):\n\n''Memorial slab no. 11, walled grave, contains 3 coffins. Here rests with God the noble and honorable Isaak Byschoff, former Hospital Master, died peacefully on 2 November 1709. At the age of 67 years minus ... months. Awaiting his Blissful resurrection in Jesus Christ. Here rests with God the honorable and virtuous Catharina Gyssendorfferin, housemistress, wife of Isaak Byschoff, the former Hospital Master. Died blissfully on 9 August ao 1697, aged 41 years. Awaiting blissful resurrection. (105)''\n\nThe number 105 references the memorial slab register of the Barf\u00fcsser Church of 1771, containing 110 family gravesites and information about the buried. It is kept in the State Archive of Basel City as StABS Bauakten JJ 32 bis 33\u2019. In position 105 for the gravesite of the Hospital Master Bischoff, it is noted that his granddaughter Anna Catharina Bischoff was buried in August 1787.\n\nMoreover, Blendinger noted:\n\n''N.b. Under this slab there was a walled grave (without soil), wherein 2 black and one yellow coffins, all well-preserved, were located. In the two black coffins were male, in the yellow one a small female corpse. They were all well preserved and resembled mummies, for their bodies were dried out only, their clothes still pleated; hair, teeth and fingernails still intact. Once they were taken out and inspected, they were buried again in the crypt, but covered with soil.\n''\nThus for the first time there was a name for the mummy. Blendinger's description of the \"small female corpse\" coincides with the mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff exhumed in 1975 for the second time.\n\n==Genealogy== \n[[File:Boris Johnson official portrait (cropped).jpg |thumb|upright|A descendant of the Barf\u00fcsser Church lady: the UK Prime Minister and Fromer Mayor of London [[Boris Johnson]]]]\n\nA research team of the Institute of Mummy Research of [[Eurac Research]] in [[Bozen]] succeeded in isolating the [[Mitochondrion|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of the mummy and identifying a variant of the [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|haplogroup U]], providing the basis for scientific identification. Female descendants of the mummy needed to be found to compare their saliva with the mummy's DNA. The team of genealogists of Basel's citizen-researchers undertook this painstaking task and drew a family tree of the female line with information drawn from church and marriage records and internet groups.  (A further project of the Citizen Science was, for example, the research on [[Theo the Pipe Smoker]].)\n\nJustina Froben, born 1512, was identified as Anna Catharina Bischoff's oldest ancestor, seven generations back: the daughter of the printer [[Johann Froben]] in Basel. From her, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin were able to reconstruct an uninterrupted female line over 15 generations, from the beginning of the 16th century to Rosemary Probst-Ryhiner in the present. A second line was identified in the US, to where one of Anna Catharina Bischoff's descendants had emigrated in the 19th century. DNA samples of both families were [[Genealogical DNA test|analysed]], both revealing a coincidence with the mummy's DNA of over 99.8%. It was thereby proven that Anna Catharina Bischoff, born on 23 March 1719 in Strasburg, was buried on 30 August 1787 in Basel.<ref> Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nA direct connection through Anna Catharina Bischoff's son-in-law Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein leads to the British politician [[Boris Johnson]]; his great-grandmother was Marie Luise [[Pfeffel family|von Pfeffel]].<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch. 25. Januar 2018 (german)]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/-a-1189665.html ''Das ist die Ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-Oma von Boris Johnson.'' Spiegel Online, 25. Januar 2018]</ref> A [[ABC World News Tonight|World News BBC]] team travelled to the media event in Basel's Natural History Museum in January 2018 to report on the forebear of the prominent politician.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 www.bbc.com, 28 january 2018]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=\"10\"|Relationship with Boris Johnson\n|- bgcolor=\"FFDD88\"align=\"center\"\n| align=left | '''wedding''' || \u26ad 1738 || \u26ad 1759 || \u26ad 1808 || \u26ad 1836|| \u26ad um 1800|| \u26ad 1906|| \u26ad1936|| \u26ad 1963|| \n|- align=left\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center | '''f'''||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Anna Catharina Bischoff'''<br/>1719\u20131787|| Anna Katharina Gernler<br/>1739\u20131776|| Carolina von Tettenborn<br/>1789\u20131811|| Karoline von Rothenburg<br/>1805\u20131872|| H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re<br/>1862\u20131951\n|| Marie Louise von Pfeffel<br/>1882\u20131944|| Yvonne Eileen Williams<br/>1907\u20131987|| Charlotte Fawcett<br/>* 1942||\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center |'''m''' || Lucas Gernler <br/>1704\u20131781||[[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein]]<br/>1726\u20131807||Christian von Pfeffel<br/>1765\u20131834||Karl Max von Pfeffel<br/>1811\u20131890|| Hubert von Pfeffel<br/>1843\u20131922|| Stanley Fred Williams<br/>1880\u20131955|| Osman Johnson Kemal<br/>1909\u20131992|| [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]]<br/>* 1940||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Boris Johnson]]'''<br/>* 1964\n|}\n\n==Life==\nAnna Catharina Bischoff, granddaughter to Hospital Master Isaak Bischoff, stemmed from an old Basel lineage. She was born on 23 March 1719 as the oldest of five siblings, of which only her younger sister Anna Margaretha survived past childhood. Her parents were the reformed pastor Johann Jakob Bischoff (1683\u20131733) and Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt (1697\u20131735). The family was well-off and lived in the centre of Strasbourg in a ten-room, two-story house with a maid.\n\nHer father died in 1733 aged 49, when Anna Catharina was 14. The same year, the widow Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt returned with her two young daughters to Basel, her city of origin. Just before the move, Anna Catharina met her future husband, Lucas Gernler (1704\u20131781), 15 years her senior. In 1732/33 he acted as a substitute for her father in [[Wolfisheim]], where services were held. Later, he would be his successor.\n\nAfter their wedding in 1738 in Basel, the couple returned to Strasbourg, where Anna Catherina gave birth to seven children, of which only two daughters survived past childhood. Augusta remained single and the other, Anna Katharina Gernler (1739\u20131776), married the German historian and diplomat Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein. She died in Versailles in 1776 aged 37.\n\nIn 1781, Lucas Gernler died from a stroke aged 77, leaving behind countless letters and a church [[hymnal]]; a year later, Anna Catharina, then 62, moved to Basel. Until her death she likely lived with her younger sister Anna Margareta Geym\u00fcller-Bischoff (1724\u20131804), who had married a wealthy trader.<ref>Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nAnna Catharina's great-grandson Karl Maximilian von Pfeffel (1811\u20131890) later married the illegitimate daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]], Karoline von Rothenburg. The couple are the great-great-grandparents of Boris Johnson, who thereby is a descendant of the lady of the Barf\u00fcsser Church in the seventh generation.<ref>[https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html nmbs.ch]</ref>\n\n==Open questions==\nA team of 40 from the fields of [[anthropology]], [[genealogy]], [[Forensic science|forensic medicine]], [[molecular biology]], [[history of medicine]] and [[toxicology]] conducted the research underpinning the identification of the dead woman. Despite these comprehensive inquiries, several questions remain open, such as:\n* What is the significance of the striking position of the hands?\n* What happened to the two mummies of males mentioned 1843 by Blendinger?\n* What is the origin of the skeleton found in 1975 in the upper coffin? The skull belongs to a roughly 25-year-old man, the rest of the skeleton to a roughly 40-year-old woman. It could be the remains of Catharina's grandmother Catharina Gysend\u00f6rffer, buried in 1697 aged 41. The identity of the male, to whom the skull belonged, has not been ascertained.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 82</ref>\n* Was there a correspondence between Anna Catharina Bischoff and her daughter Katharina Gernler (1739-1776)? If yes, in which archive could the letters been found?\n* Is there a portrait of Anna Catharina Bischoff and her husband Lucas Gernler?\n\nThe team keeps researching with the objective to answer the open questions and to make the life and work of Anna Catharina Bischoff available to a wider interested public in form of a book. The research is undertaken in cooperation with the History Department of the [[University of Basel]] and coordinated at the Basel's Museum of Natural History.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anna Catharina Bischoff}}\n* [https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html Natural History Museum of Basel: photos, family tree]\n* [https://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/basler-mumie-von-1787-ist-mit-britischem-aussenminister-verwandt-ld.1351046 Alois Feusi, Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, january 2018]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/25/remains-in-europe-mummified-woman-in-basel-is-boris-johnsons-ancestor Guardian, january 2018]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bischoff, Anna Catharina}}\n[[Category:1719 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Basel-Stadt]]\n[[Category:Mummies]]\n'Anna Catharina Bischoff''' (born 23 March 1719 in [[Strasbourg]] and buried 30 August 1787 in [[Basel]]), also known as the \"Lady (or mummy) of the Barf\u00fcsser Church\" was the wife of the [[pastor]] Lucas Gernler. She gained popularity in 1975, when her [[Mummy|mummified]] corpse was found in a shaft at the Barf\u00fcsser Church in Basel.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 bbc news]</ref>\n\n==Past history==\n[[File:Barfuesserplatz 1788.jpg|thumb|Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1788]]\n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1835.jpg|thumb|Around 1835, when the church was used as a warehouse]]\n\nIn 1975, the Barf\u00fcsser Church underwent a thorough renovation, during which the archaeological department of the city of Basel excavated and documented hundreds of burial sites.\n\n==Discovery==\nOn 20 October 1975, workers discovered a brick-walled grave chamber in front of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]], containing two well-preserved coffins sitting on a pile of bones. The upper coffin contained the skeleton of a female while the smaller coffin beneath contained the completely mummified corpse of a woman, who would later be known as the \"Lady/Mummy of the Barf\u00fcsser Church.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/boris-johnson-mummy-swiss-corpse-relative-dna-anna-catharina-bischoff-syphilis-uk-foreign-secretary-a8177641.html Independent.co.uk 25 january 2018]</ref>\n\n==First examinations==\nThe woman was buried in a simple spruce wood coffin, her left hand holding her right arm above the wrist. The mummy was mostly intact: only the head and feet had decomposed while parts of her dress and hair were conserved. Her height was 142&nbsp;cm, which is small even by contemporary standards; skinfolds point at a stout body.\n\nA first examination in 1976 by [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Bruno Kaufmann revealed that [[Mercury sulfide]] (found in the whole body, especially in the lungs), prevented decay and was responsible for the mummification. Atmospheric conditions within the coffin and grave chamber also prevented [[microbes]] from breaking down the corpse.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 76ff (german)</ref>\n\n==Recent research==\nSince 2015, the mummy has been investigated using modern methods at the [[Natural History Museum of Basel]]. [[CT scan|Computer tomography]] revealed [[atherosclerosis]] of the abdominal [[aorta]] and [[gall stones|gallstones]], pointing at a diet consisting mainly of carbohydrates and fatty meat. During her lifetime, the woman had lost all the teeth in her upper jaw due to a sugary diet and oral hygiene neglect; her lower incisors and canines, although [[Tooth decay|decayed]], were preserved.\n[[File:Behandlung mit Quecksilberd\u00e4mpfen.jpeg|thumb|Treatment with mercury vapour. In a small chamber, mercury vapour was inhaled. Illustration of the 17th century]]\n\nThe detection of [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] in the lungs and other organs of Anna Catharina Bischoff led the medical historians of the 1970s to the conclusion that the woman had undergone a mercury inhalation therapy. In those days, it was the usual method of treatment, which, however, was only administered to patients with severe cases of [[syphilis]].<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Anna-Catharina/6000000044219255864 geni.com]</ref>\n\nModern analytical methods for measuring the level of mercury exposure indicate that the amount administered was below the threshold to have caused [[mercury poisoning]]. Mercury was indeed found in the body of Anna Catharina Bischoff, but with the data available at present, it is not possible to ascertain whether this had actually led to her death. Thus, the cause of her death cannot be proven beyond doubt. Further investigation is necessary to indicate whether this was caused by the syphilis or a combination of syphilis and mercury exposure. <ref>Report Thomas Briellmann, forensic toxicologist, University Basel</ref>\n\n==Identification== \n[[File:Aktennotiz Blendinger.jpg|thumb|upright|File note by contractor Blendinger]]\nAccording to the prominent position of her grave, it can be deduced that the deceased was a member of a privileged class\u2014the location was reserved for members of the high clergy or dignitaries.<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch of 25 january 2018 (German)]</ref>\n \nChurch archive documents show that the shaft in front of the choir had been opened once before 1843 when the nave of the church was transformed into a commercial warehouse. When the workers lifted the memorial slab labeled number 11, they discovered a grave underneath with three coffins. In 2016, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin, members of Basel's citizen-researchers who discover and transcribe historic sources, discovered the relevant text in contractor Blendinger's notes, describing the text on the memorial slab as follows (in the original in German):\n\n''Memorial slab no. 11, walled grave, contains 3 coffins. Here rests with God the noble and honorable Isaak Byschoff, former Hospital Master, died peacefully on 2 November 1709. At the age of 67 years minus ... months. Awaiting his Blissful resurrection in Jesus Christ. Here rests with God the honorable and virtuous Catharina Gyssendorfferin, housemistress, wife of Isaak Byschoff, the former Hospital Master. Died blissfully on 9 August ao 1697, aged 41 years. Awaiting blissful resurrection. (105)''\n\nThe number 105 references the memorial slab register of the Barf\u00fcsser Church of 1771, containing 110 family gravesites and information about the buried. It is kept in the State Archive of Basel City as StABS Bauakten JJ 32 bis 33\u2019. In position 105 for the gravesite of the Hospital Master Bischoff, it is noted that his granddaughter Anna Catharina Bischoff was buried in August 1787.\n\nMoreover, Blendinger noted:\n\n''N.b. Under this slab there was a walled grave (without soil), wherein 2 black and one yellow coffins, all well-preserved, were located. In the two black coffins were male, in the yellow one a small female corpse. They were all well preserved and resembled mummies, for their bodies were dried out only, their clothes still pleated; hair, teeth and fingernails still intact. Once they were taken out and inspected, they were buried again in the crypt, but covered with soil.\n''\nThus for the first time there was a name for the mummy. Blendinger's description of the \"small female corpse\" coincides with the mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff exhumed in 1975 for the second time.\n\n==Genealogy== \n[[File:Boris Johnson official portrait (cropped).jpg |thumb|upright|A descendant of the Barf\u00fcsser Church lady: the UK Prime Minister and Fromer Mayor of London [[Boris Johnson]]]]\n\nA research team of the Institute of Mummy Research of [[Eurac Research]] in [[Bozen]] succeeded in isolating the [[Mitochondrion|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of the mummy and identifying a variant of the [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|haplogroup U]], providing the basis for scientific identification. Female descendants of the mummy needed to be found to compare their saliva with the mummy's DNA. The team of genealogists of Basel's citizen-researchers undertook this painstaking task and drew a family tree of the female line with information drawn from church and marriage records and internet groups.  (A further project of the Citizen Science was, for example, the research on [[Theo the Pipe Smoker]].)\n\nJustina Froben, born 1512, was identified as Anna Catharina Bischoff's oldest ancestor, seven generations back: the daughter of the printer [[Johann Froben]] in Basel. From her, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin were able to reconstruct an uninterrupted female line over 15 generations, from the beginning of the 16th century to Rosemary Probst-Ryhiner in the present. A second line was identified in the US, to where one of Anna Catharina Bischoff's descendants had emigrated in the 19th century. DNA samples of both families were [[Genealogical DNA test|analysed]], both revealing a coincidence with the mummy's DNA of over 99.8%. It was thereby proven that Anna Catharina Bischoff, born on 23 March 1719 in Strasburg, was buried on 30 August 1787 in Basel.<ref> Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nA direct connection through Anna Catharina Bischoff's son-in-law Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein leads to the British politician [[Boris Johnson]]; his great-grandmother was Marie Luise [[Pfeffel family|von Pfeffel]].<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch. 25. Januar 2018 (german)]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/-a-1189665.html ''Das ist die Ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-Oma von Boris Johnson.'' Spiegel Online, 25. Januar 2018]</ref> A [[ABC World News Tonight|World News BBC]] team travelled to the media event in Basel's Natural History Museum in January 2018 to report on the forebear of the prominent politician.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 www.bbc.com, 28 january 2018]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=\"10\"|Relationship with Boris Johnson\n|- bgcolor=\"FFDD88\"align=\"center\"\n| align=left | '''wedding''' || \u26ad 1738 || \u26ad 1759 || \u26ad 1808 || \u26ad 1836|| \u26ad um 1800|| \u26ad 1906|| \u26ad1936|| \u26ad 1963|| \n|- align=left\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center | '''f'''||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Anna Catharina Bischoff'''<br/>1719\u20131787|| Anna Katharina Gernler<br/>1739\u20131776|| Carolina von Tettenborn<br/>1789\u20131811|| Karoline von Rothenburg<br/>1805\u20131872|| H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re<br/>1862\u20131951\n|| Marie Louise von Pfeffel<br/>1882\u20131944|| Yvonne Eileen Williams<br/>1907\u20131987|| Charlotte Fawcett<br/>* 1942||\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center |'''m''' || Lucas Gernler <br/>1704\u20131781||[[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein]]<br/>1726\u20131807||Christian von Pfeffel<br/>1765\u20131834||Karl Max von Pfeffel<br/>1811\u20131890|| Hubert von Pfeffel<br/>1843\u20131922|| Stanley Fred Williams<br/>1880\u20131955|| Osman Johnson Kemal<br/>1909\u20131992|| [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]]<br/>* 1940||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Boris Johnson]]'''<br/>* 1964\n|}\n\n==Life==\nAnna Catharina Bischoff, granddaughter to Hospital Master Isaak Bischoff, stemmed from an old Basel lineage. She was born on 23 March 1719 as the oldest of five siblings, of which only her younger sister Anna Margaretha survived past childhood. Her parents were the reformed pastor Johann Jakob Bischoff (1683\u20131733) and Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt (1697\u20131735). The family was well-off and lived in the centre of Strasbourg in a ten-room, two-story house with a maid.\n\nHer father died in 1733 aged 49, when Anna Catharina was 14. The same year, the widow Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt returned with her two young daughters to Basel, her city of origin. Just before the move, Anna Catharina met her future husband, Lucas Gernler (1704\u20131781), 15 years her senior. In 1732/33 he acted as a substitute for her father in [[Wolfisheim]], where services were held. Later, he would be his successor.\n\nAfter their wedding in 1738 in Basel, the couple returned to Strasbourg, where Anna Catherina gave birth to seven children, of which only two daughters survived past childhood. Augusta remained single and the other, Anna Katharina Gernler (1739\u20131776), married the German historian and diplomat Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein. She died in Versailles in 1776 aged 37.\n\nIn 1781, Lucas Gernler died from a stroke aged 77, leaving behind countless letters and a church [[hymnal]]; a year later, Anna Catharina, then 62, moved to Basel. Until her death she likely lived with her younger sister Anna Margareta Geym\u00fcller-Bischoff (1724\u20131804), who had married a wealthy trader.<ref>Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nAnna Catharina's great-grandson Karl Maximilian von Pfeffel (1811\u20131890) later married the illegitimate daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]], Karoline von Rothenburg. The couple are the great-great-grandparents of Boris Johnson, who thereby is a descendant of the lady of the Barf\u00fcsser Church in the seventh generation.<ref>[https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html nmbs.ch]</ref>\n\n==Open questions==\nA team of 40 from the fields of [[anthropology]], [[genealogy]], [[Forensic science|forensic medicine]], [[molecular biology]], [[history of medicine]] and [[toxicology]] conducted the research underpinning the identification of the dead woman. Despite these comprehensive inquiries, several questions remain open, such as:\n* What is the significance of the striking position of the hands?\n* What happened to the two mummies of males mentioned 1843 by Blendinger?\n* What is the origin of the skeleton found in 1975 in the upper coffin? The skull belongs to a roughly 25-year-old man, the rest of the skeleton to a roughly 40-year-old woman. It could be the remains of Catharina's grandmother Catharina Gysend\u00f6rffer, buried in 1697 aged 41. The identity of the male, to whom the skull belonged, has not been ascertained.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 82</ref>\n* Was there a correspondence between Anna Catharina Bischoff and her daughter Katharina Gernler (1739-1776)? If yes, in which archive could the letters been found?\n* Is there a portrait of Anna Catharina Bischoff and her husband Lucas Gernler?\n\nThe team keeps researching with the objective to answer the open questions and to make the life and work of Anna Catharina Bischoff available to a wider interested public in form of a book. The research is undertaken in cooperation with the History Department of the [[University of Basel]] and coordinated at the Basel's Museum of Natural History.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anna Catharina Bischoff}}\n* [https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html Natural History Museum of Basel: photos, family tree]\n* [https://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/basler-mumie-von-1787-ist-mit-britischem-aussenminister-verwandt-ld.1351046 Alois Feusi, Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, january 2018]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/25/remains-in-europe-mummified-woman-in-basel-is-boris-johnsons-ancestor Guardian, january 2018]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bischoff, Anna Catharina}}\n[[Category:1719 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Basel-Stadt]]\n[[Category:Mummies]]\n'Anna Catharina Bischoff''' (born 23 March 1719 in [[Strasbourg]] and buried 30 August 1787 in [[Basel]]), also known as the \"Lady (or mummy) of the Barf\u00fcsser Church\" was the wife of the [[pastor]] Lucas Gernler. She gained popularity in 1975, when her [[Mummy|mummified]] corpse was found in a shaft at the Barf\u00fcsser Church in Basel.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 bbc news]</ref>\n\n==Past history==\n[[File:Barfuesserplatz 1788.jpg|thumb|Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1788]]\n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1835.jpg|thumb|Around 1835, when the church was used as a warehouse]]\n\nIn 1975, the Barf\u00fcsser Church underwent a thorough renovation, during which the archaeological department of the city of Basel excavated and documented hundreds of burial sites.\n\n==Discovery==\nOn 20 October 1975, workers discovered a brick-walled grave chamber in front of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]], containing two well-preserved coffins sitting on a pile of bones. The upper coffin contained the skeleton of a female while the smaller coffin beneath contained the completely mummified corpse of a woman, who would later be known as the \"Lady/Mummy of the Barf\u00fcsser Church.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/boris-johnson-mummy-swiss-corpse-relative-dna-anna-catharina-bischoff-syphilis-uk-foreign-secretary-a8177641.html Independent.co.uk 25 january 2018]</ref>\n\n==First examinations==\nThe woman was buried in a simple spruce wood coffin, her left hand holding her right arm above the wrist. The mummy was mostly intact: only the head and feet had decomposed while parts of her dress and hair were conserved. Her height was 142&nbsp;cm, which is small even by contemporary standards; skinfolds point at a stout body.\n\nA first examination in 1976 by [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Bruno Kaufmann revealed that [[Mercury sulfide]] (found in the whole body, especially in the lungs), prevented decay and was responsible for the mummification. Atmospheric conditions within the coffin and grave chamber also prevented [[microbes]] from breaking down the corpse.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 76ff (german)</ref>\n\n==Recent research==\nSince 2015, the mummy has been investigated using modern methods at the [[Natural History Museum of Basel]]. [[CT scan|Computer tomography]] revealed [[atherosclerosis]] of the abdominal [[aorta]] and [[gall stones|gallstones]], pointing at a diet consisting mainly of carbohydrates and fatty meat. During her lifetime, the woman had lost all the teeth in her upper jaw due to a sugary diet and oral hygiene neglect; her lower incisors and canines, although [[Tooth decay|decayed]], were preserved.\n[[File:Behandlung mit Quecksilberd\u00e4mpfen.jpeg|thumb|Treatment with mercury vapour. In a small chamber, mercury vapour was inhaled. Illustration of the 17th century]]\n\nThe detection of [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] in the lungs and other organs of Anna Catharina Bischoff led the medical historians of the 1970s to the conclusion that the woman had undergone a mercury inhalation therapy. In those days, it was the usual method of treatment, which, however, was only administered to patients with severe cases of [[syphilis]].<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Anna-Catharina/6000000044219255864 geni.com]</ref>\n\nModern analytical methods for measuring the level of mercury exposure indicate that the amount administered was below the threshold to have caused [[mercury poisoning]]. Mercury was indeed found in the body of Anna Catharina Bischoff, but with the data available at present, it is not possible to ascertain whether this had actually led to her death. Thus, the cause of her death cannot be proven beyond doubt. Further investigation is necessary to indicate whether this was caused by the syphilis or a combination of syphilis and mercury exposure. <ref>Report Thomas Briellmann, forensic toxicologist, University Basel</ref>\n\n==Identification== \n[[File:Aktennotiz Blendinger.jpg|thumb|upright|File note by contractor Blendinger]]\nAccording to the prominent position of her grave, it can be deduced that the deceased was a member of a privileged class\u2014the location was reserved for members of the high clergy or dignitaries.<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch of 25 january 2018 (German)]</ref>\n \nChurch archive documents show that the shaft in front of the choir had been opened once before 1843 when the nave of the church was transformed into a commercial warehouse. When the workers lifted the memorial slab labeled number 11, they discovered a grave underneath with three coffins. In 2016, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin, members of Basel's citizen-researchers who discover and transcribe historic sources, discovered the relevant text in contractor Blendinger's notes, describing the text on the memorial slab as follows (in the original in German):\n\n''Memorial slab no. 11, walled grave, contains 3 coffins. Here rests with God the noble and honorable Isaak Byschoff, former Hospital Master, died peacefully on 2 November 1709. At the age of 67 years minus ... months. Awaiting his Blissful resurrection in Jesus Christ. Here rests with God the honorable and virtuous Catharina Gyssendorfferin, housemistress, wife of Isaak Byschoff, the former Hospital Master. Died blissfully on 9 August ao 1697, aged 41 years. Awaiting blissful resurrection. (105)''\n\nThe number 105 references the memorial slab register of the Barf\u00fcsser Church of 1771, containing 110 family gravesites and information about the buried. It is kept in the State Archive of Basel City as StABS Bauakten JJ 32 bis 33\u2019. In position 105 for the gravesite of the Hospital Master Bischoff, it is noted that his granddaughter Anna Catharina Bischoff was buried in August 1787.\n\nMoreover, Blendinger noted:\n\n''N.b. Under this slab there was a walled grave (without soil), wherein 2 black and one yellow coffins, all well-preserved, were located. In the two black coffins were male, in the yellow one a small female corpse. They were all well preserved and resembled mummies, for their bodies were dried out only, their clothes still pleated; hair, teeth and fingernails still intact. Once they were taken out and inspected, they were buried again in the crypt, but covered with soil.\n''\nThus for the first time there was a name for the mummy. Blendinger's description of the \"small female corpse\" coincides with the mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff exhumed in 1975 for the second time.\n\n==Genealogy== \n[[File:Boris Johnson official portrait (cropped).jpg |thumb|upright|A descendant of the Barf\u00fcsser Church lady: the UK Prime Minister and Fromer Mayor of London [[Boris Johnson]]]]\n\nA research team of the Institute of Mummy Research of [[Eurac Research]] in [[Bozen]] succeeded in isolating the [[Mitochondrion|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of the mummy and identifying a variant of the [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|haplogroup U]], providing the basis for scientific identification. Female descendants of the mummy needed to be found to compare their saliva with the mummy's DNA. The team of genealogists of Basel's citizen-researchers undertook this painstaking task and drew a family tree of the female line with information drawn from church and marriage records and internet groups.  (A further project of the Citizen Science was, for example, the research on [[Theo the Pipe Smoker]].)\n\nJustina Froben, born 1512, was identified as Anna Catharina Bischoff's oldest ancestor, seven generations back: the daughter of the printer [[Johann Froben]] in Basel. From her, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin were able to reconstruct an uninterrupted female line over 15 generations, from the beginning of the 16th century to Rosemary Probst-Ryhiner in the present. A second line was identified in the US, to where one of Anna Catharina Bischoff's descendants had emigrated in the 19th century. DNA samples of both families were [[Genealogical DNA test|analysed]], both revealing a coincidence with the mummy's DNA of over 99.8%. It was thereby proven that Anna Catharina Bischoff, born on 23 March 1719 in Strasburg, was buried on 30 August 1787 in Basel.<ref> Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nA direct connection through Anna Catharina Bischoff's son-in-law Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein leads to the British politician [[Boris Johnson]]; his great-grandmother was Marie Luise [[Pfeffel family|von Pfeffel]].<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch. 25. Januar 2018 (german)]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/-a-1189665.html ''Das ist die Ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-Oma von Boris Johnson.'' Spiegel Online, 25. Januar 2018]</ref> A [[ABC World News Tonight|World News BBC]] team travelled to the media event in Basel's Natural History Museum in January 2018 to report on the forebear of the prominent politician.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 www.bbc.com, 28 january 2018]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=\"10\"|Relationship with Boris Johnson\n|- bgcolor=\"FFDD88\"align=\"center\"\n| align=left | '''wedding''' || \u26ad 1738 || \u26ad 1759 || \u26ad 1808 || \u26ad 1836|| \u26ad um 1800|| \u26ad 1906|| \u26ad1936|| \u26ad 1963|| \n|- align=left\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center | '''f'''||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Anna Catharina Bischoff'''<br/>1719\u20131787|| Anna Katharina Gernler<br/>1739\u20131776|| Carolina von Tettenborn<br/>1789\u20131811|| Karoline von Rothenburg<br/>1805\u20131872|| H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re<br/>1862\u20131951\n|| Marie Louise von Pfeffel<br/>1882\u20131944|| Yvonne Eileen Williams<br/>1907\u20131987|| Charlotte Fawcett<br/>* 1942||\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center |'''m''' || Lucas Gernler <br/>1704\u20131781||[[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein]]<br/>1726\u20131807||Christian von Pfeffel<br/>1765\u20131834||Karl Max von Pfeffel<br/>1811\u20131890|| Hubert von Pfeffel<br/>1843\u20131922|| Stanley Fred Williams<br/>1880\u20131955|| Osman Johnson Kemal<br/>1909\u20131992|| [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]]<br/>* 1940||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Boris Johnson]]'''<br/>* 1964\n|}\n\n==Life==\nAnna Catharina Bischoff, granddaughter to Hospital Master Isaak Bischoff, stemmed from an old Basel lineage. She was born on 23 March 1719 as the oldest of five siblings, of which only her younger sister Anna Margaretha survived past childhood. Her parents were the reformed pastor Johann Jakob Bischoff (1683\u20131733) and Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt (1697\u20131735). The family was well-off and lived in the centre of Strasbourg in a ten-room, two-story house with a maid.\n\nHer father died in 1733 aged 49, when Anna Catharina was 14. The same year, the widow Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt returned with her two young daughters to Basel, her city of origin. Just before the move, Anna Catharina met her future husband, Lucas Gernler (1704\u20131781), 15 years her senior. In 1732/33 he acted as a substitute for her father in [[Wolfisheim]], where services were held. Later, he would be his successor.\n\nAfter their wedding in 1738 in Basel, the couple returned to Strasbourg, where Anna Catherina gave birth to seven children, of which only two daughters survived past childhood. Augusta remained single and the other, Anna Katharina Gernler (1739\u20131776), married the German historian and diplomat Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein. She died in Versailles in 1776 aged 37.\n\nIn 1781, Lucas Gernler died from a stroke aged 77, leaving behind countless letters and a church [[hymnal]]; a year later, Anna Catharina, then 62, moved to Basel. Until her death she likely lived with her younger sister Anna Margareta Geym\u00fcller-Bischoff (1724\u20131804), who had married a wealthy trader.<ref>Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nAnna Catharina's great-grandson Karl Maximilian von Pfeffel (1811\u20131890) later married the illegitimate daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]], Karoline von Rothenburg. The couple are the great-great-grandparents of Boris Johnson, who thereby is a descendant of the lady of the Barf\u00fcsser Church in the seventh generation.<ref>[https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html nmbs.ch]</ref>\n\n==Open questions==\nA team of 40 from the fields of [[anthropology]], [[genealogy]], [[Forensic science|forensic medicine]], [[molecular biology]], [[history of medicine]] and [[toxicology]] conducted the research underpinning the identification of the dead woman. Despite these comprehensive inquiries, several questions remain open, such as:\n* What is the significance of the striking position of the hands?\n* What happened to the two mummies of males mentioned 1843 by Blendinger?\n* What is the origin of the skeleton found in 1975 in the upper coffin? The skull belongs to a roughly 25-year-old man, the rest of the skeleton to a roughly 40-year-old woman. It could be the remains of Catharina's grandmother Catharina Gysend\u00f6rffer, buried in 1697 aged 41. The identity of the male, to whom the skull belonged, has not been ascertained.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 82</ref>\n* Was there a correspondence between Anna Catharina Bischoff and her daughter Katharina Gernler (1739-1776)? If yes, in which archive could the letters been found?\n* Is there a portrait of Anna Catharina Bischoff and her husband Lucas Gernler?\n\nThe team keeps researching with the objective to answer the open questions and to make the life and work of Anna Catharina Bischoff available to a wider interested public in form of a book. The research is undertaken in cooperation with the History Department of the [[University of Basel]] and coordinated at the Basel's Museum of Natural History.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anna Catharina Bischoff}}\n* [https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html Natural History Museum of Basel: photos, family tree]\n* [https://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/basler-mumie-von-1787-ist-mit-britischem-aussenminister-verwandt-ld.1351046 Alois Feusi, Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, january 2018]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/25/remains-in-europe-mummified-woman-in-basel-is-boris-johnsons-ancestor Guardian, january 2018]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bischoff, Anna Catharina}}\n[[Category:1719 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Basel-Stadt]]\n[[Category:Mummies]]\n'Anna Catharina Bischoff''' (born 23 March 1719 in [[Strasbourg]] and buried 30 August 1787 in [[Basel]]), also known as the \"Lady (or mummy) of the Barf\u00fcsser Church\" was the wife of the [[pastor]] Lucas Gernler. She gained popularity in 1975, when her [[Mummy|mummified]] corpse was found in a shaft at the Barf\u00fcsser Church in Basel.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 bbc news]</ref>\n\n==Past history==\n[[File:Barfuesserplatz 1788.jpg|thumb|Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1788]]\n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1835.jpg|thumb|Around 1835, when the church was used as a warehouse]]\n\nIn 1975, the Barf\u00fcsser Church underwent a thorough renovation, during which the archaeological department of the city of Basel excavated and documented hundreds of burial sites.\n\n==Discovery==\nOn 20 October 1975, workers discovered a brick-walled grave chamber in front of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]], containing two well-preserved coffins sitting on a pile of bones. The upper coffin contained the skeleton of a female while the smaller coffin beneath contained the completely mummified corpse of a woman, who would later be known as the \"Lady/Mummy of the Barf\u00fcsser Church.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/boris-johnson-mummy-swiss-corpse-relative-dna-anna-catharina-bischoff-syphilis-uk-foreign-secretary-a8177641.html Independent.co.uk 25 january 2018]</ref>\n\n==First examinations==\nThe woman was buried in a simple spruce wood coffin, her left hand holding her right arm above the wrist. The mummy was mostly intact: only the head and feet had decomposed while parts of her dress and hair were conserved. Her height was 142&nbsp;cm, which is small even by contemporary standards; skinfolds point at a stout body.\n\nA first examination in 1976 by [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Bruno Kaufmann revealed that [[Mercury sulfide]] (found in the whole body, especially in the lungs), prevented decay and was responsible for the mummification. Atmospheric conditions within the coffin and grave chamber also prevented [[microbes]] from breaking down the corpse.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 76ff (german)</ref>\n\n==Recent research==\nSince 2015, the mummy has been investigated using modern methods at the [[Natural History Museum of Basel]]. [[CT scan|Computer tomography]] revealed [[atherosclerosis]] of the abdominal [[aorta]] and [[gall stones|gallstones]], pointing at a diet consisting mainly of carbohydrates and fatty meat. During her lifetime, the woman had lost all the teeth in her upper jaw due to a sugary diet and oral hygiene neglect; her lower incisors and canines, although [[Tooth decay|decayed]], were preserved.\n[[File:Behandlung mit Quecksilberd\u00e4mpfen.jpeg|thumb|Treatment with mercury vapour. In a small chamber, mercury vapour was inhaled. Illustration of the 17th century]]\n\nThe detection of [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] in the lungs and other organs of Anna Catharina Bischoff led the medical historians of the 1970s to the conclusion that the woman had undergone a mercury inhalation therapy. In those days, it was the usual method of treatment, which, however, was only administered to patients with severe cases of [[syphilis]].<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Anna-Catharina/6000000044219255864 geni.com]</ref>\n\nModern analytical methods for measuring the level of mercury exposure indicate that the amount administered was below the threshold to have caused [[mercury poisoning]]. Mercury was indeed found in the body of Anna Catharina Bischoff, but with the data available at present, it is not possible to ascertain whether this had actually led to her death. Thus, the cause of her death cannot be proven beyond doubt. Further investigation is necessary to indicate whether this was caused by the syphilis or a combination of syphilis and mercury exposure. <ref>Report Thomas Briellmann, forensic toxicologist, University Basel</ref>\n\n==Identification== \n[[File:Aktennotiz Blendinger.jpg|thumb|upright|File note by contractor Blendinger]]\nAccording to the prominent position of her grave, it can be deduced that the deceased was a member of a privileged class\u2014the location was reserved for members of the high clergy or dignitaries.<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch of 25 january 2018 (German)]</ref>\n \nChurch archive documents show that the shaft in front of the choir had been opened once before 1843 when the nave of the church was transformed into a commercial warehouse. When the workers lifted the memorial slab labeled number 11, they discovered a grave underneath with three coffins. In 2016, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin, members of Basel's citizen-researchers who discover and transcribe historic sources, discovered the relevant text in contractor Blendinger's notes, describing the text on the memorial slab as follows (in the original in German):\n\n''Memorial slab no. 11, walled grave, contains 3 coffins. Here rests with God the noble and honorable Isaak Byschoff, former Hospital Master, died peacefully on 2 November 1709. At the age of 67 years minus ... months. Awaiting his Blissful resurrection in Jesus Christ. Here rests with God the honorable and virtuous Catharina Gyssendorfferin, housemistress, wife of Isaak Byschoff, the former Hospital Master. Died blissfully on 9 August ao 1697, aged 41 years. Awaiting blissful resurrection. (105)''\n\nThe number 105 references the memorial slab register of the Barf\u00fcsser Church of 1771, containing 110 family gravesites and information about the buried. It is kept in the State Archive of Basel City as StABS Bauakten JJ 32 bis 33\u2019. In position 105 for the gravesite of the Hospital Master Bischoff, it is noted that his granddaughter Anna Catharina Bischoff was buried in August 1787.\n\nMoreover, Blendinger noted:\n\n''N.b. Under this slab there was a walled grave (without soil), wherein 2 black and one yellow coffins, all well-preserved, were located. In the two black coffins were male, in the yellow one a small female corpse. They were all well preserved and resembled mummies, for their bodies were dried out only, their clothes still pleated; hair, teeth and fingernails still intact. Once they were taken out and inspected, they were buried again in the crypt, but covered with soil.\n''\nThus for the first time there was a name for the mummy. Blendinger's description of the \"small female corpse\" coincides with the mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff exhumed in 1975 for the second time.\n\n==Genealogy== \n[[File:Boris Johnson official portrait (cropped).jpg |thumb|upright|A descendant of the Barf\u00fcsser Church lady: the UK Prime Minister and Fromer Mayor of London [[Boris Johnson]]]]\n\nA research team of the Institute of Mummy Research of [[Eurac Research]] in [[Bozen]] succeeded in isolating the [[Mitochondrion|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of the mummy and identifying a variant of the [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|haplogroup U]], providing the basis for scientific identification. Female descendants of the mummy needed to be found to compare their saliva with the mummy's DNA. The team of genealogists of Basel's citizen-researchers undertook this painstaking task and drew a family tree of the female line with information drawn from church and marriage records and internet groups.  (A further project of the Citizen Science was, for example, the research on [[Theo the Pipe Smoker]].)\n\nJustina Froben, born 1512, was identified as Anna Catharina Bischoff's oldest ancestor, seven generations back: the daughter of the printer [[Johann Froben]] in Basel. From her, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin were able to reconstruct an uninterrupted female line over 15 generations, from the beginning of the 16th century to Rosemary Probst-Ryhiner in the present. A second line was identified in the US, to where one of Anna Catharina Bischoff's descendants had emigrated in the 19th century. DNA samples of both families were [[Genealogical DNA test|analysed]], both revealing a coincidence with the mummy's DNA of over 99.8%. It was thereby proven that Anna Catharina Bischoff, born on 23 March 1719 in Strasburg, was buried on 30 August 1787 in Basel.<ref> Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nA direct connection through Anna Catharina Bischoff's son-in-law Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein leads to the British politician [[Boris Johnson]]; his great-grandmother was Marie Luise [[Pfeffel family|von Pfeffel]].<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch. 25. Januar 2018 (german)]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/-a-1189665.html ''Das ist die Ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-Oma von Boris Johnson.'' Spiegel Online, 25. Januar 2018]</ref> A [[ABC World News Tonight|World News BBC]] team travelled to the media event in Basel's Natural History Museum in January 2018 to report on the forebear of the prominent politician.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 www.bbc.com, 28 january 2018]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=\"10\"|Relationship with Boris Johnson\n|- bgcolor=\"FFDD88\"align=\"center\"\n| align=left | '''wedding''' || \u26ad 1738 || \u26ad 1759 || \u26ad 1808 || \u26ad 1836|| \u26ad um 1800|| \u26ad 1906|| \u26ad1936|| \u26ad 1963|| \n|- align=left\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center | '''f'''||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Anna Catharina Bischoff'''<br/>1719\u20131787|| Anna Katharina Gernler<br/>1739\u20131776|| Carolina von Tettenborn<br/>1789\u20131811|| Karoline von Rothenburg<br/>1805\u20131872|| H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re<br/>1862\u20131951\n|| Marie Louise von Pfeffel<br/>1882\u20131944|| Yvonne Eileen Williams<br/>1907\u20131987|| Charlotte Fawcett<br/>* 1942||\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center |'''m''' || Lucas Gernler <br/>1704\u20131781||[[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein]]<br/>1726\u20131807||Christian von Pfeffel<br/>1765\u20131834||Karl Max von Pfeffel<br/>1811\u20131890|| Hubert von Pfeffel<br/>1843\u20131922|| Stanley Fred Williams<br/>1880\u20131955|| Osman Johnson Kemal<br/>1909\u20131992|| [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]]<br/>* 1940||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Boris Johnson]]'''<br/>* 1964\n|}\n\n==Life==\nAnna Catharina Bischoff, granddaughter to Hospital Master Isaak Bischoff, stemmed from an old Basel lineage. She was born on 23 March 1719 as the oldest of five siblings, of which only her younger sister Anna Margaretha survived past childhood. Her parents were the reformed pastor Johann Jakob Bischoff (1683\u20131733) and Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt (1697\u20131735). The family was well-off and lived in the centre of Strasbourg in a ten-room, two-story house with a maid.\n\nHer father died in 1733 aged 49, when Anna Catharina was 14. The same year, the widow Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt returned with her two young daughters to Basel, her city of origin. Just before the move, Anna Catharina met her future husband, Lucas Gernler (1704\u20131781), 15 years her senior. In 1732/33 he acted as a substitute for her father in [[Wolfisheim]], where services were held. Later, he would be his successor.\n\nAfter their wedding in 1738 in Basel, the couple returned to Strasbourg, where Anna Catherina gave birth to seven children, of which only two daughters survived past childhood. Augusta remained single and the other, Anna Katharina Gernler (1739\u20131776), married the German historian and diplomat Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein. She died in Versailles in 1776 aged 37.\n\nIn 1781, Lucas Gernler died from a stroke aged 77, leaving behind countless letters and a church [[hymnal]]; a year later, Anna Catharina, then 62, moved to Basel. Until her death she likely lived with her younger sister Anna Margareta Geym\u00fcller-Bischoff (1724\u20131804), who had married a wealthy trader.<ref>Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nAnna Catharina's great-grandson Karl Maximilian von Pfeffel (1811\u20131890) later married the illegitimate daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]], Karoline von Rothenburg. The couple are the great-great-grandparents of Boris Johnson, who thereby is a descendant of the lady of the Barf\u00fcsser Church in the seventh generation.<ref>[https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html nmbs.ch]</ref>\n\n==Open questions==\nA team of 40 from the fields of [[anthropology]], [[genealogy]], [[Forensic science|forensic medicine]], [[molecular biology]], [[history of medicine]] and [[toxicology]] conducted the research underpinning the identification of the dead woman. Despite these comprehensive inquiries, several questions remain open, such as:\n* What is the significance of the striking position of the hands?\n* What happened to the two mummies of males mentioned 1843 by Blendinger?\n* What is the origin of the skeleton found in 1975 in the upper coffin? The skull belongs to a roughly 25-year-old man, the rest of the skeleton to a roughly 40-year-old woman. It could be the remains of Catharina's grandmother Catharina Gysend\u00f6rffer, buried in 1697 aged 41. The identity of the male, to whom the skull belonged, has not been ascertained.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 82</ref>\n* Was there a correspondence between Anna Catharina Bischoff and her daughter Katharina Gernler (1739-1776)? If yes, in which archive could the letters been found?\n* Is there a portrait of Anna Catharina Bischoff and her husband Lucas Gernler?\n\nThe team keeps researching with the objective to answer the open questions and to make the life and work of Anna Catharina Bischoff available to a wider interested public in form of a book. The research is undertaken in cooperation with the History Department of the [[University of Basel]] and coordinated at the Basel's Museum of Natural History.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anna Catharina Bischoff}}\n* [https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html Natural History Museum of Basel: photos, family tree]\n* [https://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/basler-mumie-von-1787-ist-mit-britischem-aussenminister-verwandt-ld.1351046 Alois Feusi, Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, january 2018]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/25/remains-in-europe-mummified-woman-in-basel-is-boris-johnsons-ancestor Guardian, january 2018]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bischoff, Anna Catharina}}\n[[Category:1719 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Basel-Stadt]]\n[[Category:Mummies]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Anna_Catharina_Bischoff.jpeg|thumb|Mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff]] \n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserkirche Treppe Fundort.jpeg|thumb|Where the coffin was found]]\n'''Anna Catharina Bischoff''' (born 23 March 1719 in [[Strasbourg]] and buried 30 August 1787 in [[Basel]]), also known as the \"Lady (or mummy) of the Barf\u00fcsser Church\" was the wife of the [[pastor]] Lucas Gernler. She gained popularity in 1975, when her [[Mummy|mummified]] corpse was found in a shaft at the Barf\u00fcsser Church in Basel.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 bbc news]</ref>\n\n==Past history==\n[[File:Barfuesserplatz 1788.jpg|thumb|Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1788]]\n[[File:Barf\u00fcsserplatz 1835.jpg|thumb|Around 1835, when the church was used as a warehouse]]\n\nIn 1975, the Barf\u00fcsser Church underwent a thorough renovation, during which the archaeological department of the city of Basel excavated and documented hundreds of burial sites.\n\n==Discovery==\nOn 20 October 1975, workers discovered a brick-walled grave chamber in front of the [[Choir (architecture)|choir]], containing two well-preserved coffins sitting on a pile of bones. The upper coffin contained the skeleton of a female while the smaller coffin beneath contained the completely mummified corpse of a woman, who would later be known as the \"Lady/Mummy of the Barf\u00fcsser Church.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/boris-johnson-mummy-swiss-corpse-relative-dna-anna-catharina-bischoff-syphilis-uk-foreign-secretary-a8177641.html Independent.co.uk 25 january 2018]</ref>\n\n==First examinations==\nThe woman was buried in a simple spruce wood coffin, her left hand holding her right arm above the wrist. The mummy was mostly intact: only the head and feet had decomposed while parts of her dress and hair were conserved. Her height was 142&nbsp;cm, which is small even by contemporary standards; skinfolds point at a stout body.\n\nA first examination in 1976 by [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] Bruno Kaufmann revealed that [[Mercury sulfide]] (found in the whole body, especially in the lungs), prevented decay and was responsible for the mummification. Atmospheric conditions within the coffin and grave chamber also prevented [[microbes]] from breaking down the corpse.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 76ff (german)</ref>\n\n==Recent research==\nSince 2015, the mummy has been investigated using modern methods at the [[Natural History Museum of Basel]]. [[CT scan|Computer tomography]] revealed [[atherosclerosis]] of the abdominal [[aorta]] and [[gall stones|gallstones]], pointing at a diet consisting mainly of carbohydrates and fatty meat. During her lifetime, the woman had lost all the teeth in her upper jaw due to a sugary diet and oral hygiene neglect; her lower incisors and canines, although [[Tooth decay|decayed]], were preserved.\n[[File:Behandlung mit Quecksilberd\u00e4mpfen.jpeg|thumb|Treatment with mercury vapour. In a small chamber, mercury vapour was inhaled. Illustration of the 17th century]]\n\nThe detection of [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] in the lungs and other organs of Anna Catharina Bischoff led the medical historians of the 1970s to the conclusion that the woman had undergone a mercury inhalation therapy. In those days, it was the usual method of treatment, which, however, was only administered to patients with severe cases of [[syphilis]].<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Anna-Catharina/6000000044219255864 geni.com]</ref>\n\nModern analytical methods for measuring the level of mercury exposure indicate that the amount administered was below the threshold to have caused [[mercury poisoning]]. Mercury was indeed found in the body of Anna Catharina Bischoff, but with the data available at present, it is not possible to ascertain whether this had actually led to her death. Thus, the cause of her death cannot be proven beyond doubt. Further investigation is necessary to indicate whether this was caused by the syphilis or a combination of syphilis and mercury exposure. <ref>Report Thomas Briellmann, forensic toxicologist, University Basel</ref>\n\n==Identification== \n[[File:Aktennotiz Blendinger.jpg|thumb|upright|File note by contractor Blendinger]]\nAccording to the prominent position of her grave, it can be deduced that the deceased was a member of a privileged class\u2014the location was reserved for members of the high clergy or dignitaries.<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch of 25 january 2018 (German)]</ref>\n \nChurch archive documents show that the shaft in front of the choir had been opened once before 1843 when the nave of the church was transformed into a commercial warehouse. When the workers lifted the memorial slab labeled number 11, they discovered a grave underneath with three coffins. In 2016, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin, members of Basel's citizen-researchers who discover and transcribe historic sources, discovered the relevant text in contractor Blendinger's notes, describing the text on the memorial slab as follows (in the original in German):\n\n''Memorial slab no. 11, walled grave, contains 3 coffins. Here rests with God the noble and honorable Isaak Byschoff, former Hospital Master, died peacefully on 2 November 1709. At the age of 67 years minus ... months. Awaiting his Blissful resurrection in Jesus Christ. Here rests with God the honorable and virtuous Catharina Gyssendorfferin, housemistress, wife of Isaak Byschoff, the former Hospital Master. Died blissfully on 9 August ao 1697, aged 41 years. Awaiting blissful resurrection. (105)''\n\nThe number 105 references the memorial slab register of the Barf\u00fcsser Church of 1771, containing 110 family gravesites and information about the buried. It is kept in the State Archive of Basel City as StABS Bauakten JJ 32 bis 33\u2019. In position 105 for the gravesite of the Hospital Master Bischoff, it is noted that his granddaughter Anna Catharina Bischoff was buried in August 1787.\n\nMoreover, Blendinger noted:\n\n''N.b. Under this slab there was a walled grave (without soil), wherein 2 black and one yellow coffins, all well-preserved, were located. In the two black coffins were male, in the yellow one a small female corpse. They were all well preserved and resembled mummies, for their bodies were dried out only, their clothes still pleated; hair, teeth and fingernails still intact. Once they were taken out and inspected, they were buried again in the crypt, but covered with soil.\n''\nThus for the first time there was a name for the mummy. Blendinger's description of the \"small female corpse\" coincides with the mummy of Anna Catharina Bischoff exhumed in 1975 for the second time.\n\n==Genealogy== \n[[File:Boris Johnson official portrait (cropped).jpg |thumb|upright|A descendant of the Barf\u00fcsser Church lady: the UK Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]]]\n\nA research team of the Institute of Mummy Research of [[Eurac Research]] in [[Bozen]] succeeded in isolating the [[Mitochondrion|mitochondrial]] [[DNA]] of the mummy and identifying a variant of the [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|haplogroup U]], providing the basis for scientific identification. Female descendants of the mummy needed to be found to compare their saliva with the mummy's DNA. The team of genealogists of Basel's citizen-researchers undertook this painstaking task and drew a family tree of the female line with information drawn from church and marriage records and internet groups.  (A further project of the Citizen Science was, for example, the research on [[Theo the Pipe Smoker]].)\n\nJustina Froben, born 1512, was identified as Anna Catharina Bischoff's oldest ancestor, seven generations back: the daughter of the printer [[Johann Froben]] in Basel. From her, Marie-Louise Gamma and Diana Gysin were able to reconstruct an uninterrupted female line over 15 generations, from the beginning of the 16th century to Rosemary Probst-Ryhiner in the present. A second line was identified in the US, to where one of Anna Catharina Bischoff's descendants had emigrated in the 19th century. DNA samples of both families were [[Genealogical DNA test|analysed]], both revealing a coincidence with the mummy's DNA of over 99.8%. It was thereby proven that Anna Catharina Bischoff, born on 23 March 1719 in Strasburg, was buried on 30 August 1787 in Basel.<ref> Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nA direct connection through Anna Catharina Bischoff's son-in-law Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein leads to the British politician [[Boris Johnson]]; his great-grandmother was Marie Luise [[Pfeffel family|von Pfeffel]].<ref>[https://www.bzbasel.ch/basel/basel-stadt/die-identitaet-der-basler-barfuesser-mumie-ist-entschluesselt-die-blutlinie-fuehrt-in-bekannte-kreise-132128489 www.bzbasel.ch. 25. Januar 2018 (german)]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/-a-1189665.html ''Das ist die Ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-ur-Oma von Boris Johnson.'' Spiegel Online, 25. Januar 2018]</ref> A [[ABC World News Tonight|World News BBC]] team travelled to the media event in Basel's Natural History Museum in January 2018 to report on the forebear of the prominent politician.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42805485 www.bbc.com, 28 january 2018]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! colspan=\"10\"|Relationship with Boris Johnson\n|- bgcolor=\"FFDD88\"align=\"center\"\n| align=left | '''wedding''' || \u26ad 1738 || \u26ad 1759 || \u26ad 1808 || \u26ad 1836|| \u26ad um 1800|| \u26ad 1906|| \u26ad1936|| \u26ad 1963|| \n|- align=left\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center | '''f'''||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Anna Catharina Bischoff'''<br/>1719\u20131787|| Anna Katharina Gernler<br/>1739\u20131776|| Carolina von Tettenborn<br/>1789\u20131811|| Karoline von Rothenburg<br/>1805\u20131872|| H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Arnous de Rivi\u00e8re<br/>1862\u20131951\n|| Marie Louise von Pfeffel<br/>1882\u20131944|| Yvonne Eileen Williams<br/>1907\u20131987|| Charlotte Fawcett<br/>* 1942||\n|- bgcolor=\"FFFFDD\n| align=center |'''m''' || Lucas Gernler <br/>1704\u20131781||[[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein]]<br/>1726\u20131807||Christian von Pfeffel<br/>1765\u20131834||Karl Max von Pfeffel<br/>1811\u20131890|| Hubert von Pfeffel<br/>1843\u20131922|| Stanley Fred Williams<br/>1880\u20131955|| Osman Johnson Kemal<br/>1909\u20131992|| [[Stanley Johnson (writer)|Stanley Johnson]]<br/>* 1940||class=\"hintergrundfarbe7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Boris Johnson]]'''<br/>* 1964\n|}\n\n==Life==\nAnna Catharina Bischoff, granddaughter to Hospital Master Isaak Bischoff, stemmed from an old Basel lineage. She was born on 23 March 1719 as the oldest of five siblings, of which only her younger sister Anna Margaretha survived past childhood. Her parents were the reformed pastor Johann Jakob Bischoff (1683\u20131733) and Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt (1697\u20131735). The family was well-off and lived in the centre of Strasbourg in a ten-room, two-story house with a maid.\n\nHer father died in 1733 aged 49, when Anna Catharina was 14. The same year, the widow Augusta Margaretha Burckhardt returned with her two young daughters to Basel, her city of origin. Just before the move, Anna Catharina met her future husband, Lucas Gernler (1704\u20131781), 15 years her senior. In 1732/33 he acted as a substitute for her father in [[Wolfisheim]], where services were held. Later, he would be his successor.\n\nAfter their wedding in 1738 in Basel, the couple returned to Strasbourg, where Anna Catherina gave birth to seven children, of which only two daughters survived past childhood. Augusta remained single and the other, Anna Katharina Gernler (1739\u20131776), married the German historian and diplomat Christian Friedrich Pfeffel von Kriegelstein. She died in Versailles in 1776 aged 37.\n\nIn 1781, Lucas Gernler died from a stroke aged 77, leaving behind countless letters and a church [[hymnal]]; a year later, Anna Catharina, then 62, moved to Basel. Until her death she likely lived with her younger sister Anna Margareta Geym\u00fcller-Bischoff (1724\u20131804), who had married a wealthy trader.<ref>Gerhard Hotz et al.: Der r\u00e4tselhafte Mumienfund aus der Barf\u00fcsserkirche in Basel; Schweizerische Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Familienforschung in der Schweiz; Jahrbuch 2018, Vol. 45, S. 35\u201364</ref>\n\nAnna Catharina's great-grandson Karl Maximilian von Pfeffel (1811\u20131890) later married the illegitimate daughter of [[Prince Paul of W\u00fcrttemberg]], Karoline von Rothenburg. The couple are the great-great-grandparents of Boris Johnson, who thereby is a descendant of the lady of the Barf\u00fcsser Church in the seventh generation.<ref>[https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html nmbs.ch]</ref>\n\n==Open questions==\nA team of 40 from the fields of [[anthropology]], [[genealogy]], [[Forensic science|forensic medicine]], [[molecular biology]], [[history of medicine]] and [[toxicology]] conducted the research underpinning the identification of the dead woman. Despite these comprehensive inquiries, several questions remain open, such as:\n* What is the significance of the striking position of the hands?\n* What happened to the two mummies of males mentioned 1843 by Blendinger?\n* What is the origin of the skeleton found in 1975 in the upper coffin? The skull belongs to a roughly 25-year-old man, the rest of the skeleton to a roughly 40-year-old woman. It could be the remains of Catharina's grandmother Catharina Gysend\u00f6rffer, buried in 1697 aged 41. The identity of the male, to whom the skull belonged, has not been ascertained.<ref>Spektrum der Wissenschaft; Spezial Arch\u00e4ologie - Geschichte - Kultur 3/2018, S. 82</ref>\n* Was there a correspondence between Anna Catharina Bischoff and her daughter Katharina Gernler (1739-1776)? If yes, in which archive could the letters been found?\n* Is there a portrait of Anna Catharina Bischoff and her husband Lucas Gernler?\n\nThe team keeps researching with the objective to answer the open questions and to make the life and work of Anna Catharina Bischoff available to a wider interested public in form of a book. The research is undertaken in cooperation with the History Department of the [[University of Basel]] and coordinated at the Basel's Museum of Natural History.\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anna Catharina Bischoff}}\n* [https://www.nmbs.ch/home/info_angebote/mediencorner/pressebilder/barfuessermumie.html Natural History Museum of Basel: photos, family tree]\n* [https://www.nzz.ch/schweiz/basler-mumie-von-1787-ist-mit-britischem-aussenminister-verwandt-ld.1351046 Alois Feusi, Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, january 2018]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/25/remains-in-europe-mummified-woman-in-basel-is-boris-johnsons-ancestor Guardian, january 2018]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bischoff, Anna Catharina}}\n[[Category:1719 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Basel-Stadt]]\n[[Category:Mummies]]\n", "name_user": "2606:a000:e5cf:7c00:a432:56b6:3e4d:45fe", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna_Catharina_Bischoff"}
